column15: Description
Facebook introducted its "Community Standards" for the first time
A new tool that helps users make decisions about their privacy settings
Facebook decided to remove misleading manipulated media that fits certain criteria
Facebook introduces new features that inform the user of third party logins and informs users about how their information is being used
Introduction of policies regarding COVID-19. Facebook decides to remove misinformation and conspiracy theories as well as provide credible information
This update to Messenger Kids gave parents more access to their childrens' app usage.
Facebook releases more data to independent academic researchers.
Facebook allows U.S. based political candidates to release branded content.
Facebook publishes a white paper offering questions and suggesstions about how to manage content in the future.
Facebook blocks Singapore-based users' access to the State Times' Review due to an order from the Singaporean government
Facebook prohibits ads that guarantee a coronavirus cure or create a sense of panic.
Mark Zuckerberg posts update in which he says Facebook is giving unlimited free add space to the WHO and is sharing anonymized user data to help track the spread of the virus.
Facebook bans advertisements for medical face masks
Facebook introduces a business resources hub to provide information to businesses and expands access to local alerts.
Facebook makes a joint statement with Google, Microsoft, Twitter, LinkdenIn, Reddit, and Youtube
Facebook launches a $100 million grant program for small businesses and a $1 million grant porgram for fact checkers.
Facebook launches an information hub on the Facebook app to provide up to date information about the coronavirus.
Facebook offers 12 months of free Workplace Advanced to government agencies and emergency service providers.
Facebook bans advertisements for hand sanitzer, disinfecting wipes, and COVID-19 testing kits.
Facebook starts an initiative to help government agenicies broadcast their message on Facebook.
Facebook requires authorization to run ads about election or social issues in specific countries.
An overview of Facebook's policies to combat misninformation about Coronavirus.
Facebook launches a digital literacy program to provide resources and training to help people navigate the intenet safely.
Facebook invests $100 million in the news industry
Facebook updates its data access tools to allow users to access more data about their app usage and the information they interact with.
Facebook donates $25 million to support health care workers.
Facebook adds an ads experiment feature to allow users to test different advertising strategies.
Facebook updates video publishing to make it easier and more accessible.
Facebook launches Community Help to allow users to seek and offer help to thei local communities.
Facebook updates its policies on protecting the census and removing suppressive information.
Facebook announces new tools to help researchers track the virus.
Facebook expands local alerts and provides information pop-ups in COVID-19 related groups.
Facebook introduces new tools and resources to promote well-being including new access to a mental health live series and quiet mode.
Facebook prevents advertisements from appearing on Audience Network in-stream videos or websites.
Facebook helps the WHO launch an interactive experience on Messenger that allows users to get timely and reliable information.
Facebook updates its approach to preventing coronavirus misinformation and begins informing users via notifications if they have interacted with misinformation.
Facebook releases a symptom map and continues to gather data to update the map.
Facebook allows free access to their patenets to help promote innovation.
Facebook begins tagging high-reach profiles' posts with information regarding the accounts origin country to increase transparency.
Facebook reverses an ad policy that centralized ad spending in a central Campaign Budget Optimization system
Facebook introduces Messenger Rooms
Facebook expands Community Help
Facebook launches Businesses Nearby to allow users to see posts from nearby businesses.
Facebook releases its community standards enforcement report.
Facebook expands brand safety controls for advertisers
Facebook introduces Facebook shops to help small businesses sell products online.
Facebook updates its guidelines on music usage in videos.
Facebook allows users to post content on the Creator Studio App
Twitter introduces Promoted Trend Spotlight for advertisers.
A summary of Twitter's protection of Taiwan's election including banning political advertisements and introducing a specific hashtag.
Twitter begins suggesting credible news sources when users search for coronavirus.
Twitter announces its approach to manipulated media including guidelines on what content will be labeled and what content will be removed.
Twitter provides internet safety training aroung the world throughout the month of February
Twitter introduces a dedicated census search tool and increases efforts to remove misinformation regarding the census.
Twitter expands its coronavirus search function, increases efforts to remove manipulative content, and bans innaproporiate advertisements.
Twitter updates its policies regarding hateful speech.
Twitter updates its policies regarding COVID-19 to further prevent misinformation and remove tweets that deny information from trusted agencies or promote unsafe practices.
Twitter increases its reliance on automated technology to perform content regulation.
Twitter begins verifying accounts providing reliable COVID-19 information.
Twitter announces a grant program to support journalism during COVID-19.
Twitter supports the COVID-19 Global Hackathon, an opportunity to develop software solutions with positive social impacts.
Twitter updates its guidelines concerning content regulation. Twitter decides to remove content that denies safety information from trusted agenices as well as content that could harm public health.
Tiwtter broadens its definition of harmful content  to include more unverified claims and content that can incite people to action.
Twitter allows advertisements that implicitly or in some cases explicitly mention COVID-19.
Twitter in collaboration with other technology companies creates a new site to provide resources for those experiencing a substance use disorder.
Twitter prohibits unverified claims regarding coronavirus that could incite people to action.
Twitter promotes information regarding the environment in support of Earth Day.
Twitter introduces new policies to both protect discussion of the Korean election and to promote engagement with it
Twitter introduces new labels and warnings on tweets that contain coronavirus misinformation
Twitter releases official guidelines regarding what bots are and what uses of bots are prohibited.
Twitter introduces new conversation control settings that allow users to control replies on their posts
Twitter announces new initiative to prevent internet shutdowns around the world.
Twitter releases its Inclusion and Diversity report.

Youtube treats personal information from anyone watching children's conent on the platform as coming from a child. On videos made for kids, Youtube limits data collection and use, resulting in the restriction of certain product features. Also, Youtube will promote Youtube Kids across all made for kids content.

column3: 2 things: First, the policy change itself is dated March 11, 2020. But, the content of the post detailing the policy change says "starting in February." Second, there is a local element to this too that I think is worth flagging. The countries/regions where this info panel is available are Germany, South Korea, Spain, the United Kingdom, and the United States. Reference URL 2 provides some information as to where the information comes from.
column15: Youtube launches info panels that drive users to the WHO or to lical resources that reflect local government guidelines. Youtube says they'll donate ad inventory to governments and NGOs in impacted regions to use for education and information.

Youtube is taking the steps needed to prioritize the well-being of their employees, particularly through relying more on technology to help with the work normally done by reviewers. Youtube cautions that this may result in increased video removals, including videos that may not violate policies. Creators can appeal the decision to remove the video. Youtube will also be cautious about what content gets promoted, and in some cases, unreviewed content may not be availabe via search, on the homepage, or in recommendations.
Youtube tells its users to expect longer than usual wait times for responses to questions across all forms of support including email, chat, and social.

column3: Content in this news shelf is populated algorithmically, using hundreds of signals, including relevance to COVID-19, how up-to-date it is, and region. Flagging region aspect - could be interesting.
column15: Youtube introduces a COVID-19 news shelf that may show on the Youtube homepage.
Due to impact of the coronavrius on the Youtube workforce, Community posts are unavailable on some channels.
Youtube launches Learn@Home, a website with learning resources and content for family.

column10: European Union, United Kingdom, and Switzerland
column15: Youtube defaults all videos on their platform to standard definition in the EU, UK, and CH.
Youtube defaults all videos on their platform to standard definition, globally.

Youtube launches additional health panels for COVID-19 that show in search results for COVID-19 related searches. Specifically, Youtube is trying to prioritize local health sources, so may provide a link to a local health authority alongisde the health panel.
Youtube expands the monetization of content mentioning or feauturing COVID-19 to all creators and news organizations.

To assist faith organizations everywhere who are new to online services, Youtube has brought together helpful information to get started with live streaming. In particular, there are a set of tutorials in a playlist (last updated May 5, 2020).
Youtube introduces a destination button on the Explore tab for content from creators participating in the #StayHome #WithMe campaign.
Youtube Originals announces slate of new content amidst COVID-19 #WithMe initiatives

column10: United States specific - only available in Brazil, India, and USA - nowhere else, thus far
column15: Youtube continues to improve the news experience on their platform in the United States by expanding fact check information panels that were first launched in Brazil and India in 2019.
Youtube launches a link to a COVID-19 assessment in their COVID-19 health panel in Search to help people make decisions about seeking appropriate medical care.
Youtube Music officially invites Google Play Music listeners to transfer their music libraries, personal taste preferences and playlists to YouTube Music.

Youtube updates its Community Guidelines to include a page on COVID-19 misinformation. In particular, misinformation includes information that contradicts the WHO or local health authorities' medical information about COVID-19.

column3: Clarity on how TikTok defines harmful or unsafe content. A point on global vs. local mentioned in the article - "Our global guidelines are the basis of the moderation policies TikTok's regional and country teams localize and implement in accordance with local laws and norms."
column15: TikTok releases a comprehensive, expanded publication of the Community Guidelines.

TikTok adds more detailed reporting options to help their community flag things for them to review; particularly, users are able to report content with deceptive information by selecting the new "misinformation category." Furthermore, TikTok will beging to surface in-app notices on election-related hashtag pages to remind users of the importance of adhering to their Community Guidelines.
TikTok adds new screen time management videos, in addition to their Screen Time Management setting that is part of the Digital Wellbeing portion of the app.

column3: One word mention of coronavirus related hashtag - not sure if that makes it enough for it to be coronavirus related.
column15: An update regarding TikTok's efforts in the US: growing their local presence, expanding their expertise, strengthening their youth safety efforts, and building in line with their values. Speicifcally, TikTok announces that they are working with third-party fact checking and media literacy organizations to counter potential misinformation. TikTok has also surfaced in-app notices related to topical issues like coronavrius or election-related content.

TikTok is protecting against exploitative content by prohibiting content that depicts or disseminates child abuse, child nudity, or sexual exploitation of children. Tiktok is promoting and supporting the implementation of the Voluntary Principles to Counter Online Child Sexual Exploitation and Abuse.

column3: This is the opening of a physical facility in Los Angeles, so not entirely sure where this stands in terms of policy/feature/operations.
column15: Tiktok to launch Transparency Center for Moderation and data practices. Update May 27 - opening of center has been delayed.

Tiktok partners with the WHO to create an informational page (along with sharing videos and livestreams from the WHO Tiktok page) on Tiktok that provides trustworthy information, offers tips on staying safe and preventing the spread of the virus, and dispels myths around COVID-19.
Tiktok introduces thhe important gathering of technology and safety experts who will help shape their policies as the founding members of Tiktok's Content Advisory Council.
Instagram begins removing hashtags used to spread false information about the coronavirus.
Instagram releases updates on internet safety day concerning misinformation, privacy, bullying and harrassment, reporting, and more.
Instagram begins removing harmful misleading information about the coronavirus.
Instagram begins promoting information from the WHO on its platform.
Instagram bans advertisements selling face masks, disinfecting wipes, and testing kits.
Instagram promotes trustworthy information about COVID-19 and begins to prohibit exploitative ads and remove false information.
Instagram shares tips and resources on how people can take care of themselves during quarantine.
Instagram introduces new features to help support small businesses.
Instagram announces its month of good to promote kindness on the app.
Instagram introduces a new feature enabling donations on Instagram live
Instagram announces new policies to combat online bullying including limiting unwanted interactions and highlighting positive comments.
Instagram introduces Guides, a way to more easily find content, information, and tips from creators.
Instagram updates its guidelines for what uses of music are allowed on the app.
Instagram introduces new ways for creators to monetize their content.
